 2. Part A – Origin and Philosophy
A1: Origin of Python
Python was developed by Guido van Rossum and released in 1991.
During that time, programming languages were complex and difficult to use. Python was designed to simplify programming and improve code readability. The main goal was to make programming accessible to everyone.
Python emphasizes clean and readable code, which helps developers write efficient programs with fewer lines of code.
________________________________________


A2: License of Python
Python is distributed under the Python Software Foundation (PSF) License.
This license allows users to:
●	Use the software freely
●	Modify the source code
●	Distribute the software
Python supports all four freedoms of open-source software:
1.	Freedom to run the program
2.	Freedom to study the source code
3.	Freedom to modify the software
4.	Freedom to distribute copies
________________________________________
A3: Ethics of Open Source
Open source software promotes collaboration and knowledge sharing. Developers from around the world contribute to improving software.
Advantages:
●	Encourages innovation
●	Builds community
●	Provides transparency
Challenges:
●	Companies may use open-source software for profit
●	Lack of centralized control
Despite challenges, open source remains a powerful model for software development.
